SSH

Secure Shell - Used to open a shell in a more secure manner than telnet

  -l - specify a username, or do user@hostname
  ssh root@webserver

  -i filename - Used for specifying what private key is used to authenticate this connection

  -F Filename Used for speicifying what configuration file to user. Default is ~/.ssh/config


ssh-keygen: script generated pub/priv keys

ssh-copy-id script will copy public key over to the target server

SSH key fingerprint - reduce chance of MITM attacks.

SSH can also tunnel GUI programs over SSH connection to be displayed on your local machine.
  ssh -X user@server


rcp has been replaced by scp
